    "Collection description": "This project records the stories of power industry workers and their families relating to Victoria’s first brown coal generated power station at Yallourn that was established in 1921 and the State Electricity Commission of Victoria's model company town of Yallourn which was completely razed to the ground by the 1980s to allow forfurther mining. The project also records the memories of the Yallourn Medical and Hospital Society, one of the first contributory health schemes to operate in Australia. In 1926 Dr James Moore Andrew took the position of the Society’s first resident medical officer and with his wife Catherine Dorothy Andrew established a family at Yallourn, practising at Yallourn Hospital and lived in Yallourn until his death in 1972. Twenty individual audio interviews were carried out with Yallourn workers and recorded in their homes along with photographs. These are now stored in mp3 audio files on Old Gippstown computers.",
